<subSubSection id="026419D0EA2ACD03D75F1D20C3FC7B4E" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="65C51193B94A36AA92D8AC6A316F50C1" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B55CDBE3DDF20BF20DDF5D04A9321A44" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
This genus is named in honor of the goddess of Aztec flowers, in Nahuatl &quot;Xōchiquetzalli&quot; (beautiful flower) &quot;xṓchitl&quot; (flower), &quot;
<normalizedToken id="EF00E32102CE21B8FA4E0204866E69AC" originalValue="quétzalli">quetzalli</normalizedToken>
&quot; (beautiful). The Aztecs developed majestic architectural works, had extensive knowledge of astronomy and great respect for nature, particularly plants.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
